<DOC><DOCNO> AP880415-0192 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-04-15-88 1808EDT</FILEID><FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     04-15 0409</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0420</SECOND><HEAD>Snow Falls in Northeast; Southwest Gets Cold Weather</HEAD><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   Snow fell Friday around the Great Lakes and over parts of NewEngland, while unseasonably chilly air settled over the desertSouthwest and heavy rain fell in Nevada and from the Plains intothe mid-Mississippi Valley.   Snow fell across much of Michigan, northern Ohio and western NewYork during the afternoon but little accumulated as temperatureswere above freezing. Snow reduced visibility to a quarter-mile atYoungstown, Ohio.   Higher elevations of Vermont got 1 to 2 inches of snow in themorning.   A winter storm watch was posted overnight for all of Vermont andparts of northeastern New York state, with up to 6 inches of snowpossible.   In the Southwest, the temperature at Yuma, Ariz., normally oneof the hottest cities in the nation, was just 56 degrees at noonwith rain. The normal high temperature at Yuma at this time of theyear is 86 degrees. Needles, Calif., at the same time was just 53degrees.   More than an inch of rain fell on parts of southern Nevadaduring the night and more locally heavy rainfall was possible.   Rain persisted from northeastern Oklahoma across the Ozarks ofsouthern Missouri and northern Arkansas to Tennessee. Temperatureswere chilly with an afternoon reading of 44 at Nashville, Tenn.Rain at Paducah, Ky., mixed with sleet in the morning.   Elsewhere, a few thunderstorms developed during the morning inTexas in the Dallas-Fort Worth area and into southeastern Oklahoma.   An overnight frost and freeze advisory was issued for northernand central sections of Illinois and a frost advisory was issued inparts of Indiana.   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 31degrees at Marquette, Mich., to 87 at Fort Stewart and Hinesville,Ga. The nation's morning low was 17 degrees at Bismarck, N.D.   For Saturday, scattered showers and thunderstorms were forecastfrom Texas across the southern Rockies and Arizona to southernIdaho. Rain and snow showers were forecast from New England to themiddle Atlantic states and the West Virginia mountains.   Highs in the 40s or 50s were predicted from the northern andmiddle Atlantic Coast states across the upper Ohio Valley to theGreat Lakes region, and in the mountains of northern Arizona; inthe 80s from Florida across the Gulf Coast region to southernTexas, and in the 60s or 70s across most of the rest of the nation.</TEXT></DOC>